\section{Skew Confluence} \label{sec:skew-confluence}

We now consider a modified grammar for \versecalc{} in which there is an additional kind of value, a \emph{fixpoint} value:
\begin{quote}
$
\begin{array}{lr@@{\;}c@@{\;}l}
      \text{Values} & |v| & ::= & |x|  \vb \hnf \vb |mu x hnf| \\
\end{array}
$
\end{quote}
and a modified set of unification rewrite rules $\mathcal{U}$ in which rule \rulename{u-occurs} is modified from
\begin{quote}
$
\begin{array}{@@{\quad}lr@@{\;}c@@{\;} l l}
  \rulename{u-occurs} & |x=V^[x]| & \movesto & |fail| & \text{if $|V| \ne |hole|$} \\
\end{array}
$
\end{quote}
to the two rules\footnote{This design allows equations to be recursive through lambda expressions but not through tuples only;
  thus equations such as |f = lam y (tup (y, f))| and |x = (tup (1,  lam y (tup (y, x))))| can be processed by rule \rulename{u-occurs-wrap},
  but the equation |x = (tup (1, x))| can be processed only by rule \rulename{u-occurs-fail}.
  An alternate design using the single rule
  \begin{quote}
$
\begin{array}{@@{\quad}lr@@{\;}c@@{\;} l l}
  \rulename{u-occurs-wrap} & |x=hnf| & \movesto & |x=mu x hnf| & \text{if $|x| \in \freevars{|hnf|}$} \\
\end{array}
$
\end{quote}
plus rule \rulename{u-unwrap} could be used instead to support recursion through tuples only as well as through lambda expressions.}
\begin{quote}
$
\begin{array}{@@{\quad}lr@@{\;}c@@{\;} l l}
  \rulename{u-occurs-fail} & |x=hnf| & \movesto & |fail| & \text{if $|x| \in \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|hnf|}$} \\
  \rulename{u-occurs-wrap} & |x=hnf| & \movesto & |x=mu x hnf| & \text{if $|x| \in \freevars{|hnf|}$ and $|x| \not\in \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|hnf|}$} \\
\end{array}
$
\end{quote}
and to which a new rewrite rule is added:
\begin{quote}
$
\begin{array}{@@{\quad}lr@@{\;}c@@{\;} l l}
  \rulename{u-unwrap} & |mu x hnf| & \movesto & |subst hnf x (mu x hnf)| \\
\end{array}
$
\end{quote}
As we will see, rule \rulename{u-unwrap} is confluent but not Noetherian.

The resulting grammar is not confluent. \guy{explain even-odd-problem}
Therefore we will modify the proof of confluence for $\runi$ to become a proof of \emph{skew confluence} \cite{Ariola2002},
and then go on to prove that \versecalc{} itself, with this modification, is skew confluent.


\subsection{Free Variables}


We use the conventional notation $\freevars{|e|}$ to denote the set of variables that occur free
in the expression |e|. Variables are bound by the constructs |def x e|, |lam x e|, and |mu x hnf|.
\Cref{fig:fvs} contains a formal definition of this function for \versecalc{}.

\begin{figure}
$
\begin{array}{r@@{\;\;}c@@{\;\;}l@@{\qquad}l}
  \freevars{|x|} & = & \{ |x| \} \\
  \freevars{|k|} & = & \{\,\} \\
  \freevars{|op|} & = & \{\,\} \\
  \freevars{|tup (v_1, commadots, v_n)|} & = & \freevars{|v_1|} \cup \cdots \cup \freevars{|v_n|} \\
  \freevars{|lam x e|} & = & \freevars{|e|} \setminus \{ x \} \\
  \freevars{|mu x e|} & = & \freevars{|e|} \setminus \{ x \} \\
  \freevars{|eu; e|} & = & \freevars{|eu|} \cup \freevars{|e|} \\
  \freevars{|v = e|} & = & \freevars{|v|} \cup \freevars{|e|} \\
  \freevars{|def x e|} & = & \freevars{|e|} \setminus \{ x \} \\
  \freevars{|fail|} & = & \{\,\}  \\
  \freevars{|e_1 choice e_2|} & = & \freevars{|e_1|} \cup \freevars{|e_2|} \\
  \freevars{|v_1 v_2|} & = & \freevars{|v_1|} \cup \freevars{|v_2|} \\
  \freevars{|one e|} & = & \freevars{|e|} \\
  \freevars{|all e|} & = & \freevars{|e|} \\
\end{array}
$
\caption{Definition of the free-variables function $\freevars{\cdot}$}\label{fig:fvs}
\end{figure}

We use the variation $\freevarsoutsidelambdas{|e|}$ to denote the set of variables that occur free
in the expression |e| in at least one position that is not within the body of a lambda expression.
As an example, $\freevarsoutsidelambdas{|def x (tup (x, f, g, lam y (tup (x, g, y, z))))|} = \{ f, g \}$ because:
\begin{itemize}
\item |x| is bound by |defKW|, so it is not free. 
\item |f| is free in a position not within the body of a lambda expression.
\item |g| is free in at least one position not within the body of a lambda expression (it also happens to be free in a second position that is within the body of a lambda expression).
\item |y| is bound by |lambda|, so it is not free. 
\item |z| is free, but appears only in a position that is within the body of a lambda expression.
\end{itemize}
\Cref{fig:fvsol} contains a formal definition of this function. It differs from the definition of $\freevars{\cdot}$
only in its handling of lambda expressions.

\begin{figure}
$
\begin{array}{r@@{\;\;}c@@{\;\;}l@@{\qquad}l}
  \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|x|} & = & \{ |x| \} \\
  \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|k|} & = & \{\,\} \\
  \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|op|} & = & \{\,\} \\
  \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|tup (v_1, commadots, v_n)|} & = & \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|v_1|} \cup \cdots \cup \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|v_n|} \\
  \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|lam x e|} & = & \{\,\} \\
  \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|mu x e|} & = & \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|e|} \setminus \{ x \} \\
  \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|eu; e|} & = & \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|eu|} \cup \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|e|} \\
  \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|v = e|} & = & \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|v|} \cup \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|e|} \\
  \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|def x e|} & = & \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|e|} \setminus \{ x \} \\
  \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|fail|} & = & \{\,\}  \\
  \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|e_1 choice e_2|} & = & \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|e_1|} \cup \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|e_2|} \\
  \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|v_1 v_2|} & = & \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|v_1|} \cup \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|v_2|} \\
  \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|one e|} & = & \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|e|} \\
  \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|all e|} & = & \freevarsoutsidelambdas{|e|} \\
\end{array}
$
\caption{Definition of the free-variables-outside-lambdas function $\freevarsoutsidelambdas{\cdot}$}\label{fig:fvsol}
\end{figure}



\subsection{Substitution}

We use the notation |subst e x v| to denote the expression that results from performing standard capture-avoiding substitution of the value |v| for every occurrence of the variable |x| within the expression |e| (it turns out that, for \versecalc{}, substitution of general expressions for variables is not required, only substitution of values for variables).
\Cref{fig:substitution} contains a formal definition of how this notation applies to the \versecalc{} grammar (compare \cite[\S 2.1.15]{Barendregt}).

\begin{figure}
$
\begin{array}{r@@{\;\;}c@@{\;\;}l@@{\qquad}l}
  |subst x x v| & \equiv & |v| \\
  |subst y x v| & \equiv & |y| & \text{if $y \neq x$}  \\
  |subst k x v| & \equiv & |k| \\
  |subst op x v| & \equiv & |op| \\
  |substNP (arr (v_1, dots, v_n)) x v| & \equiv & |arr (subst v_1 x v, dots, subst v_n x v)| \\
  |subst (lam y e) x v| & \equiv & |lam y (subst e x v)| &  \text{if $y \not\in \freevars{|x|, |v|}$ [use $\alpha$]} \\
  |subst (mu y v') x v| & \equiv & |mu y (subst v' x v)| &  \text{if $y \not\in \freevars{|x|, |v|}$ [use $\alpha$]} \\
  |subst (eu; e) x v| & \equiv &  |subst eu x v; subst e x v| \\
  |subst (v' = e) x v| & \equiv &  |subst v' x v = subst e x v| \\
  |subst (def y e) x v| & \equiv & |def y (subst e x v)| &  \text{if $y \not\in \freevars{|x|, |v|}$ [use $\alpha$]} \\
  |subst fail x v| & \equiv & |fail| \\
  |subst (e_1 choice e_2) x v| & \equiv &  |subst e_1 x v`choice`subst e_2 x v| \\
  |subst (apply1N v_1 v_2) x v| & \equiv &  |applyNP (subst v_1 x v) (subst v_2 x v)| \\
  |subst (one e) x v| & \equiv & |one (subst e x v)| \\
  |subst (all e) x v| & \equiv & |all (subst e x v)| \\
\end{array}
$
\caption{Definition of the substitution notation |subst e x v|}\label{fig:substitution}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Unwrapping of Fixpoints is Confluent but not Noetherian}

\begin{lemma}\label{lem:unwrap-confluent}
The rule \rulename{u-unwrap} is confluent.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
  Suppose that $\rstep{\rulename{u-unwrap}}{|e|}{|e_1|}$ and $\rstep{\rulename{u-unwrap}}{|e|}{|e_2|}$ for distinct redexes within $e$.
  
  If the redexes are disjoint, then \cref{lem:disjoint} applies.

  Otherwise, without loss of generality assume the redex for $\rstep{\rulename{u-unwrap}}{|e|}{|e_1|}$ contains the redex for $\rstep{\rulename{u-unwrap}}{|e|}{|e_2|}$;
  let $e$ must be of the form |C_1^[mu x (C_2^[mu y hnf])]| ($\alpha$-conversion may be used to ensure that $x$ and $y$ are distinct variables).

  Then |e_1 = C_1^[substNP (C_2^[mu y hnf]) x (mu x (C_2^[mu y hnf]))]|
  and |e_2 = C_1^[mu x (C_2^[subst hnf y (mu y hnf)])]|.

  From |e_2| we can take just one more \rulename{u-unwrap} step, using the outermost redex |mu x (C_2^[cdots])|, obtaining |e' = C_1^[subst (C_2^[subst hnf y (mu y hnf)]) x (mu x (C_2^[subst hnf y (mu y hnf)]))]|.

  \guy{More to come.}

  Thus we have $\rsteps{\rulename{u-unwrap}}{|e_1|}{|e'|}$ and $\rstep{\rulename{u-unwrap}}{|e_2|}{|e'|}$, so \rulename{u-unwrap} is strongly confluent,
  and therefore by \cref{lem:strong} is confluent.
\end{proof}

To see that \rulename{u-unwrap} is not Noetherian, observe that
$$\ensuremath{|mu x (tup (1,x))| \go{\rulename{u-unwrap}}  |tup (1, mu x (tup (1,x)))| \go{\rulename{u-unwrap}} |tup (1, (tup (1, mu x (tup (1,x)))))| \go{\rulename{u-unwrap}} \cdots}$$
is an unending sequence of reduction steps.

\subsection{Information Content}

We define a second grammar, for a second language $\vcOmega$, by adding one more value |Omega|, which indicates a lack of information as to just what will be computed.
When |Omega| appears in a context where only a value is permitted, it indicates uncertainty as to what value will be provided; 
when |Omega| appears in a context where any expression permitted, it furthermore indicates uncertainty as to how many values will be provided (possibly none).
\begin{quote}
$
\begin{array}{lr@@{\;}c@@{\;}l}
      \text{Values} & |v| & ::= & |x| \vb \hnf \vb |mu x hnf| \vb |Omega| \\
\end{array}
$
\end{quote}

For every term of \versecalc{} there is a corresponding term of $\vcOmega$, identical in structure and appearance and containing no occurrence of |Omega|;
we identify such terms and regard the set of terms of \versecalc{} as simply a subset of the terms of $\vcOmega$.

The definition of substitution (\cref{fig:substitution}) is extended in the expected trivial manner: $|subst Omega x v| \equiv |Omega|$.

\begin{definition}
(after \cite[Definition 2.3]{Ariola2002})
Let |T| be a set of terms over a signature that includes the constant |Omega|.
Define $\leqomega^T$ be the relation such that $|Omega| \leqomega^T |M|$ for every term $|M| \in |T|$;
then define $\leqomega$ to be the transitive, reflexive, and compatible closure of $\leqomega^T$.
\end{definition}

\Cref{fig:info-rewrite-rules} shows a system $\rinfo$ of rewrite rules on $\vcOmega$.
These may be compared to similar rules for the $\lambda\circ$ calculus \cite[Definition 5.20]{Ariola2002}.

\begin{figure}
 $
  \begin{array}{l}
\begin{array}{@@{\quad}lr@@{\;}c@@{\;} l l}
  \rulegroupname{Information Content:~$\rinfo${}}
  \rulename{info-fix} & |mu x v| & \movesto & |Omega| \\
  \rulename{info-seq} & |eu; e| & \movesto & |Omega| \\
  \rulename{info-exi} & |def x e| & \movesto & |Omega| \\
  \rulename{info-fail-l} & |fail choice e| & \movesto & |Omega| \\
  \rulename{info-fail-r} & |e choice fail| & \movesto & |Omega| \\
  \rulename{info-choice-omega} & |Omega choice e| & \movesto & |Omega| \\
  \rulename{info-choice-assoc} & |(e_1 choice e_2) choice e_3| & \movesto & |Omega| \\
  \rulename{info-app-omega} & |apply1N Omega v| & \movesto & |Omega| \\
  \rulename{info-app-hnf} & |apply1N hnf v| & \movesto & |Omega| \\
  \rulename{info-one} & |one e| & \movesto & |Omega| \\
  \rulename{info-all} & |all e| & \movesto & |Omega| \\
\end{array}
\end{array}
$
\caption{Rewrite rules on $\vcOmega$ for defining the function $\omegavc(e)$}\label{fig:info-rewrite-rules}
\end{figure}

\begin{lemma}\label{lem:critpairs}\cite[Lemma 3.1]{Huet80}
The relation $\go{\rr}$ is locally confluent iff for every critical pair |(e_1, e_2)| of $\rr$, |e_1| and |e_2| can be \emph{joined}---that is, there exists |e_3| such that
 $|e_1| \go{\rr} |e_3|$ and  $|e_2| \go{\rr} |e_3|$.
\end{lemma}


\begin{lemma}[$\rinfo$-Confluent] \label{lem:rinfo-c}
$\rinfo$ is locally confluent and Noetherian; therefore $\rinfo$ is confluent.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
  Consider all critical pairs of $\rinfo$:
  \begin{itemize}
\item  Rules \rulename{info-fail-l} and \rulename{info-fail-r} produce the critical pair |(Omega, Omega)|.

\item  Rules \rulename{info-fail-l} and \rulename{info-choice-omega} produce no critical pairs.

\item  Rules \rulename{info-fail-l} and \rulename{info-choice-assoc} produce the critical pair |(Omega choice e, Omega)|.

\item  Rules \rulename{info-fail-r} and \rulename{info-choice-omega} produce the critical pair |(Omega, Omega)|.

\item  Rules \rulename{info-fail-r} and \rulename{info-choice-assoc} produce the critical pairs |(Omega, Omega)| and |(Omega choice e, Omega)|.

\item  Rules \rulename{info-choice-omega} and \rulename{info-choice-assoc} produce the critical pair |(Omega choice e, Omega)|.

\item  No other pairs of rules produce any critical pairs.
\end{itemize}
The critical pair |(Omega, Omega)| can be trivially joined at |Omega|.
The critical pair |(Omega choice e, Omega)| can be joined at |Omega| in one step by using rule \rulename{info-choice-omega} on |Omega choice e|.

All critical pairs can be joined; therefore by \cref{lem:critpairs} $\rinfo$ is locally confluent.

Let the size of a term of $\vcOmega$ be the number of tokens it contains other than parentheses.
Each of the rewrite rules in \cref{fig:info-rewrite-rules} strictly decreases the number of such tokens.
Because any given term has a finite number $n$ of such tokens, and the number of tokens cannot be less than zero,
for every term every rewriting sequence from that term can have no more than $n$ steps. So $\rinfo$ is bounded and therefore Noetherian.

Because $\rinfo$ is locally confluent and Noetherian, it is confluent by Newman's lemma.
\end{proof}

Because $\rinfo$ is confluent and Noetherian, it follows that $\rinfo$ defines unique normal forms for $\vcOmega$. Therefore we are justified in defining
$\omegavc(e)$ to be the function that takes any term in $\vcOmega$ and returns the term that is its normal form under $\rinfo$.

\begin{definition}
The comparison $e \leqomegavc e'$ is defined to mean $\omegavc(e) \leqomega \omegavc(e')$.
\end{definition}
\guy{Need to prove that $\leqomegavc$ is monotonic with respect to $\leqomega$; this should be routine as per Skew paper \cite[Proposition 5.21]{Ariola2002}.}

\begin{lemma}[\versecalc{} monotonic] \label{lem:vc-monotonic}
Every rewrite rule in \versecalc{} is monotonic with respect to $\leqomegavc$.
\end{lemma}

\begin{proof}
  For every rewrite rule in $\rapp \cup \runi \cup \rcon \cup \rgc \cup \rspc$,
  the left-hand side is an expression that is mapped to |Omega| by the function $\omegavc$,
  and no matter what expression |e| is the result of applying $\omegavc$ to the right-hand side,
  we have $|Omega| \leqomega |e|$.
 \end{proof}

\subsection{Preliminaries about Skew Confluence}


\begin{definition}
  Reduction relation $\rr$ over the set of terms $T$ is \emph{skew confluent} using quasi order $\preceq$ if for all $a, b, c \in T$,
  if $a \gos{\rr} b$ and $a \gos{\rr} c$, there exists $d\in T$ such that $b \gos{\rr} d$ and $c \preceq d$. As a diagram:
  
% https://q.uiver.app/?
\[\begin{tikzcd}
	a & b \\
	c & d
	\arrow["\rr", two heads, from=1-1, to=1-2]
	\arrow[""{name=0, anchor=center, inner sep=0}, "\rr", dotted, two heads, from=1-2, to=2-2]
	\arrow[""{name=1, anchor=center, inner sep=0}, "\rr"', two heads, from=1-1, to=2-1]
	\arrow["\rr"', dotted, two heads, from=2-1, to=2-2]
	\arrow["\preceq"', no body, two heads, from=2-2, to=2-1]
	\arrow[draw=none, from=1, to=0]
\end{tikzcd}\]
\end{definition}


\subsection{New Lemmas about Skew Confluence}

\begin{lemma}
If relation $\rr$ is monotonic in some quasi order $\preceq$ and confluent, then it is skew confluent using $\preceq$.
\end{lemma}
\begin{proof}
  By the definition of confluence,
  % https://q.uiver.app/?
\[\begin{tikzcd}
	a & c \\
	b & d
	\arrow["\rr"', two heads, from=1-1, to=2-1]
	\arrow["\rr", two heads, from=1-1, to=1-2]
	\arrow["\rr", dotted, two heads, from=1-2, to=2-2]
	\arrow["\rr"', dotted, two heads, from=2-1, to=2-2]
\end{tikzcd}\]
Because $\rr$ is monotonic, $\gos{\rr} \subset \inccon{\rr}$, therefore 
% https://q.uiver.app/?
\[\begin{tikzcd}
	a & c \\
	b & d
	\arrow["\rr"', two heads, from=1-1, to=2-1]
	\arrow["\rr", two heads, from=1-1, to=1-2]
	\arrow["\rr", dotted, two heads, from=1-2, to=2-2]
	\arrow["\rr"', dotted, two heads, from=2-1, to=2-2]
	\arrow["\preceq"', no body, two heads, from=2-2, to=2-1]
\end{tikzcd}\]
\end{proof}

\begin{definition}
  Let reduction relation $\rr$ be monotonic in quasi order $\preceq$ and skew confluent using $\preceq$.
  Let reduction relation $\rr_\preceq^{\leftarrow}$ be defined by a set of rewrite rules that are converses of those rewrite rules of $\rr$ whose converses are used in the proof that $\rr$ is skew
  confluent.
  Then we say that $\rr$ is \emph{skew confluent using $\preceq$ and  $\rr_\preceq^{\leftarrow}$}.
\end{definition}


